sect4.para:
The small example illustrates the integration of the floating point library for amforth. It is based upon a conversion word >float which takes a string and tries to convert it into a float. The word fliteral compiles a floating point number into the dictionary.
: rec-float \ addr -- (f|) -1 | 0 count >float if state @ if postpone fliteral then -1 else 0 then ;
The recognizer first tries to convert the string to a number. If that fails, the flag from the >float is essentially duplicated and the recognizer is left. If the conversion succeeded, the floating point number is on the data stack. The recognizer now checks whether the number needs to be compiled or not. In any case the success flag is returned.

para.screen:
variable tick
\ this code is executed as an interrupt : timer-int-isr 1 tick +! ;
: timer-init 5 TCCR0 c! \ prescaler 1024, check data sheet ['] timer-int-isr TIMER0_OVFAddr int! 0 tick ! ;
\ turn on the timer, needs timer-init already in place : +timer 1 TIMSK c! ;
\ stops the timer : -timer 0 TIMSK c! ;
